            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1279725545,
            "creation_date": 1279717042,
            "body": "<p>You should not need to test private methods.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A private method is specifically part of the implementation. You should not test the implemenation, but the functionality. If you test the functionality a class exposes, you can change the implementation while depending on the unit test.<\/li>\n<li>If you feel the need to test a private method, this is a good sign that you should move the private method to another class and make the method public. By doing this, you get smaller classes and you can test the methods easily. If you do not want to expose this new class, you can make it package-private (the default access modifier).<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 3299443,
            "question_id": 3299405,
            "last_edit_date": 1279725545
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1bf160a6e7f3d51d74f4f3d25982b75b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 27166,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 71399,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/71399/pauljwilliams",
                "reputation": 19285,
                "display_name": "pauljwilliams",
                "accept_rate": 65
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1279717287,
            "creation_date": 1279717287,
            "body": "<p>Testing private methods implies testing implementation, rather than functionality. Think very carefully about <em>why<\/em> you want to test private methods and you may find you dont need to test them at all.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3299470,
            "question_id": 3299405
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe0ff83b10821b15e0f7fd6385be24ef?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 39261,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 113141,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/113141/justin",
                "reputation": 87295,
                "display_name": "Justin",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1279717422,
            "creation_date": 1279717422,
            "body": "<p>My personal view is that you should (wherever possible) only test behaviour that is exposed to the end user of that piece of functionality, and therefore that you should not test private methods:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>The test doesn't prove anything except to show that a piece of internal functionality is \"working\" according to something that makes no sense to the people actually using your software.  <\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>If you change / re-factor your internal implementation you could find that your unit tests start failing when in  fact the external functionality exposed has not changed at all!<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Of course you may choose to subdivide large projects up into smaller chunks of functionality, in which case you might choose to unit test the interfaces between the interfaces (for example you might choose to unit test your data access layer, despite the fact that the DAL implementation doesn't directly impact the end user).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3299492,
            "question_id": 3299405
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/991415bbb495fd7d1dcf22d037c12ef5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 47910,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 142129,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/142129/kendrick",
                "reputation": 3787,
                "display_name": "Kendrick",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1279716968,
            "creation_date": 1279716968,
            "body": "<p>You shouldn't need to test the private methods.  When you test your public methods that should, in theory, also test your private methods.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3299430,
            "question_id": 3299405
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f81c937fcdf6cced1addfc47bc508750?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
